message.content: Since "percent of a percent" deals can be tricky, we invoke some subterfuge by promoting Mary's coupon to be a discount off the regular price, resulting in $\$30-(25\%)(\$30)=\$30-\$7.50=\$22.50$. Since the two successive discounts result in $\$22.50$, then a single discount of $(\$30-\$22.50)/(\$30)\approx \boxed{25\%}$ would result in the same sale price.
